 The highest exponent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is called the degree of a polynomial.
 Some polynomials will have special properties,
 for example we will have orthogonal polynomials which have a unique property where if we use an inner product on two different orthogonal polynomials,
 it will be equal to zero.
 This property will be very useful and needed in further sections.
 Inner product will be defined as an integration over an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with a weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 We will also have a three term recurrence for orthogonal and orthonormal polynomials.
 Constants from the three term recurrence will form a Jacobi matrix and from this matrix we will obtain orthonormal polynomials and their roots.
 At the end of this chapter we will talk about quadrature rules and changing roots and weights to get Legendre polynomials if the integration we need is over a interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the weight function of this integration is 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
