 in a matrix form,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a vector representation of the Galerkin approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}$
\end_inset

 of an eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the Galerkin approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{y}\right)c\left(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}d\boldsymbol{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x},$
\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\overline{u}_{i}=\lambda_{i}^{n}W\overline{u}_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semi-definite and matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive definite.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal polynomials then 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is an identity matrix,
 leaving us with eigenvalue problem of matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
